    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The alpha-amylase and beta-amylase enzymes are key players in the starch breakdown process. Alpha-amylase is a glycosidase that breaks down starch granules into shorter chains of glucose molecules, while beta-amylase is a saccharidase that further breaks down these chains into individual glucose units.\n\nAt low hydration levels, the starch granules are more compact and harder to access, which favors the activity of alpha-amylase. This is because the enzyme can more easily penetrate the granule and break down the alpha-1,4-glycosidic bonds. As the hydration level increases, the starch granules become more hydrated and the alpha-amylase activity decreases, allowing beta-amylase to take over.\n\nBeta-amylase is more active at higher hydration levels because the increased water content allows the enzyme to access the starch granules more easily. The beta-amylase then breaks down the shorter chains produced by alpha-amylase into individual glucose units.\n\nIn a sourdough starter, the balance between alpha-amylase and beta-amylase activity is influenced by the pH and temperature. At lower pH and temperatures, alpha-amylase is more active, while at higher pH and temperatures,",
      "source": "target",
