      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the hydration level is high and beta-amylase is more active, it can lead to a shift in the metabolic pathway of the yeast. The increased availability of glucose from the starch breakdown can lead to a surge in glycolysis, which is the primary source of energy for yeast cells.\n\nHowever, if the beta-amylase activity becomes too high, it can lead to the production of glucose that is not immediately utilized by the yeast. This can result in the accumulation of glucose in the starter, which can be detrimental to the yeast's growth and survival.\n\nResearch has shown that there is a threshold beyond which the beta-amylase activity becomes the limiting factor for yeast growth. This threshold is typically around 75-80% hydration, depending on the specific yeast species and environmental conditions.\n\nAt this point, the yeast's glycolytic pathway becomes saturated, and the excess glucose is diverted towards other metabolic pathways, such as the pentose phosphate pathway or the production of other metabolic byproducts. This can lead to a decrease in yeast growth rate and an increase in the production of byproducts, such as lactic acid and ethanol.\n\nIn a sourdough starter, the optimal hydration level for yeast growth is typically around 70-75%.",
